An important nutrient in this process is Folic Acid.
Àô
Folic acid is a type of B vitamin that helps to make DNA, repair DNA and produce red blood cells (RBCs).
Àô
Folic Acid sources are brewer's yeast, blackeye peas, legumes, asparagus, walnuts, spinach and kale. ü•óü•ô
Àô
If you don‚Äôt have enough folic acid in your diet, you may end up with a folic acid deficiency. The symptoms of deficiency are often subtle and include gingivitis, depression, abnormal pap smear, fatigue, diarrhea, anemia, insomnia, irritability, forgetfulness, loss of appetite, fatigue, and shortness of breath.
Àô
Folic Acid can mask a B12 deficiency and should always be combined.
Àô
According to research, it is the #1 nutrient deficiency in the world.
Àô
If you have any questions or would like advice on the Folic Acid that you are receiving in your diet please DM me.

The popularity of meditation is increasing as more people discover its many health benefits. üòäüïä
Àô
You can use it to increase awareness of yourself and your surroundings. Many people think of it as a way to reduce stress and develop concentration.
Àô
People also use the practice to develop other beneficial habits and feelings, such as a positive mood and outlook, self-discipline, healthy sleep patterns and even increased pain tolerance.  It also brings:
Àô
- Awareness of where your conscious attention is
- Strengthened neural connections
- A 'brain break'
- Greater attention and focus
- Decreased anxiety
- To be in the present moment
Àô
One study showed that after an 8-week mindfulness course, participant MRI scans demonstrated reduced activity in the amygdala (the fight or flight centre).
Àô
Meditation has been shown in research to support the ageing brain increasing the amount of gray matter as well as supporting a healthy frontal cortex.
Àô

Vitamin K is best known for its role in the formation of clot and prevention of excessive bleeding. Vitamin K can also be used to stop heavy menstrual bleeding. In females, heavy and prolonged periods can occur as a result of a vitamin K deficiency.
Àô
Food sources where Vitamin K can be found are kale, green tea, turnip greens, spinach, broccoli and natto. ü•óüçµ
Àô
Vitamin K is beneficial for:
‚Üí clotting
‚Üí bone health by activating osteocalcin which gives bone structure
‚Üí stimulation of red blood cell formation
‚Üí reducing excessive menstrual flow
Àô
K1 is the natural form found in plants, K2 is produced in the gut where there is a healthy microbiome and K3 is the synthetic form.
Àô
Fat-Soluble vitamins like vitamin K need to be dissolved in fat for optimal absorption meaning we should eat these nutrients with fat.
Àô

So, why do you crave chocolate when you‚Äôre on your period? It's because dark chocolate contains magnesium which helps relax muscles.  So intuitively, you are reaching for something that can help you relax your muscles, decreasing any pain and cramping to help you in this time.

To help alleviate chocolate cravings, add more complex carbohydrates to your diet. Not only are they healthier, but they also help you to feel fuller, moderate your blood sugar levels and alleviate cramps. Think whole grains and legumes.
Àô
For a double dose, pick foods that are also rich in magnesium and calcium, such as leafy greens and almonds.

Vitamin E is a fat-soluble vitamin with several forms, with d-alpha-tocopherol being the natural form. Its main role is to act as an antioxidant, scavenging ‚Äúfree radicals‚Äù that cause damage to the cells.
Àô
Vitamin E prevents the damage which occurs in the arteries from free radicals (neutralizing those 'bad guys'), thereby reducing the need for cholesterol to go and patch up the problem.
Àô
Vitamin E also enhances immune function.
Àô
It is found in plant-based oils, nuts, seeds, fruits, and vegetables: ü•îüçÖ
Àô
‚Üí All polyunsaturated vegetable oils
‚Üí Sunflower seeds
‚Üí Almonds
‚Üí Peanuts, peanut butter
‚Üí Beet greens, collard greens, spinach
‚Üí Pumpkin
‚Üí Red bell pepper
‚Üí Asparagus
‚Üí Mango
‚Üí Tomatoes
‚Üí Avocado
Àô

Vitamin D is sometimes called the ‚Äúsunshine vitamin‚Äù because it‚Äôs produced in your skin in response to sunlight. It‚Äôs a fat-soluble vitamin that interacts with every single cell in the body. ‚òÄü•ö
Àô
Your body produces vitamin D naturally when it‚Äôs directly exposed to sunlight by converting the cholesterol in your skin to cholecalciferol (Vitamin D3). You can also get it through certain foods and supplements to ensure adequate levels of the vitamin in your blood. Consistent consumption of Vit D is critical as it takes approximately 3 months for the blood serum levels to increase.
Àô
Vitamin D has several important functions. Perhaps the most vital are regulating the absorption of calcium and phosphorus and facilitating normal immune system function. Getting a sufficient amount of vitamin D is important for normal growth and development of bones and teeth, as well as improved resistance against certain diseases.
Àô
Few foods contain vitamin D naturally. Because of this, some foods are fortified. This means that vitamin D has been added. Foods that contain vitamin D include:
Àô
‚Üí cod liver oil
‚Üí mackerel
‚Üí salmon
‚Üí herring
‚Üí butter
‚Üí egg yolks
‚Üí milk (fortified)
‚Üí cereal (fortified)
‚Üí yogurt (fortified)
‚Üí orange juice (fortified)
Àô
It can be hard to get enough vitamin D each day through sun exposure and food alone, so taking vitamin D supplements can help and be a great strategy for supporting heart health, reducing symptoms of depression, reducing menopause symptoms and more.
Àô

Have you heard the line, "you just need to spend more time doing self care activities"?

I am sure you have.
Self care is a massive buzz word these days.

When I am speaking with clients they say they simply don't have time to go get their nails done or soak in the tub.

And i say... WAIT!!

Did you know that self care can simply begin with making one choice just for you???

It is TRUE!!

What is one thing that would bring a smile to your face or a moment of calm and peace into your day?

Of course big things like a massage is great.

But i love to encourage women to realize that love can show up in big and small moments and it can grow from there.

node.text:
Have you put on a little extra weight in the last few months?

Are you looking for healthy ways to shift into a healthier lifestyle?

If yes, the quick fix is not the best solution. 

Quick fixes are not a long term solution. 

After all, you didn't put the weight on in one day, so choosing a solution that helps you to create long term, sustainable health habits might be an option to consider. 

I ask my clients to find patience and love for their body.

It is a miraculous vehicle for experiencing life.

Sustainable weight loss and weight management is not something that can happen overnight. 

Step 1 - Deciding weight loss is important 
Step 2 - Recognizing it will take work
Step 3 - Daily, consistent, small actions
Step 4 - Having patience and faith, that by loving your body, nurturing it and providing optimal nutrition and movement will result in the health and body you desire.

node.text:
What is the small step forward you are taking in your health today?

During a webinar yesterday, I shared the importance of committing to 1 or 2 actions per day to move the needle forward until it becomes a habit.

All too often we get pumped up about making health changes and pile on 10+ different changes in one day. 

This often leads to disappointment. Creating habits requires focus. We all know how difficult it is to focus on making 10 changes at once.

Give yourself a chance to experience success. 

Solidify 1-2 habits and then add something new.. 

Focus on moving the needle forward a little bit at a time and you will wake up one day to have created far stronger habits and a healthy lifestyle.

node.text:
Have you experienced a hot flash?

My mom calls them "tropical moments". I may seem too young for perimenopause,  but I'm not.

Did you know that the perimenopause and menopause journey can be different for everyone?

Just like anything health related. 
I watched my mom struggle with these for years.

I have seen other women flushing randomly.

Sweating profusely even when it is cold in the room.

Suffering from unrestful nights sleep.

This sucks.

I began my journey into perimenopause a couple of years ago and it was my memory challenges that appeared first.

And then the waves of heat especially at night.

But I have found something that works tremendously well for me and it may work for you as well.

Comment below if you are interested in info or DM me.

No woman should have to struggle through these internal heat waves.

Let's turn the temperature down!!
